  <!-- =========================== OT PARALLELS =========================== -->
  <section class="section" id="ot-parallels" data-section="ot-parallels">
    <div class="eyebrow">Section IX</div>
    <h1>Old Testament Parallels</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Revelation contains no direct OT quotation, yet roughly
      <strong>two-thirds of its verses contain OT allusions</strong>.
      The book cannot be read apart from the Hebrew Scriptures it
      assumes.
    </p>

    <p>
      Below are the most important OT books that supply the
      imagery of the Apocalypse, with representative parallels.
      To understand the symbols of John, one must first sit
      with the prophets he is hearing.
    </p>

    <div class="ornament">Daniel</div>
    <p>
      Daniel is the single most important OT source for Revelation —
      so much so that some scholars call the Apocalypse "a Christian
      Danielic apocalypse." Daniel's "Son of Man" (Dan 7), four beasts,
      time-times-and-half-a-time, prince of Persia, resurrection of the
      just and unjust, are all foundational.
    </p>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Daniel 7:9">Daniel 7:9</a>–10</div>
        <div class="vtext">"Thrones were placed, and the Ancient of Days took his seat… the court sat in judgment, and the books were opened."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 20:11">Revelation 20:11</a>–12</div>
        <div class="vtext">"Then I saw a great white throne and him who was seated on it… and books were opened."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Daniel 7:13">Daniel 7:13</a>–14</div>
        <div class="vtext">"One like a son of man… and to him was given dominion and glory and a kingdom."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 1:7">Revelation 1:7</a>, 13</div>
        <div class="vtext">"Behold, he is coming with the clouds… one like a son of man."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Daniel 7:7">Daniel 7:7</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"A fourth beast, terrifying and dreadful and exceedingly strong… with ten horns."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 13:1">Revelation 13:1</a>–2</div>
        <div class="vtext">"A beast rising out of the sea, with ten horns… like a leopard, its feet like a bear's."</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="ornament">Ezekiel</div>
    <p>
      Revelation borrows much of its visionary architecture from Ezekiel:
      the throne-chariot vision of chapter 1, the eating of the scroll,
      the marking of the faithful, the visions of Gog and Magog, and
      especially the new-temple vision of Ezekiel 40–48 which underlies
      Revelation's New Jerusalem.
    </p>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Ezekiel 1:5">Ezekiel 1:5</a>–10, 22, 26</div>
        <div class="vtext">"Four living creatures… each had four faces… above the firmament a throne in appearance like sapphire."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 4:2">Revelation 4:2</a>–7</div>
        <div class="vtext">"A throne stood in heaven… four living creatures… the first like a lion, the second like an ox, the third with a face like a man, the fourth like an eagle."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Ezekiel 2:9">Ezekiel 2:9</a>–<a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 3:3">Revelation 3:3</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"Behold, a hand was stretched out to me, and behold, a scroll of a book… 'Son of man, eat this scroll.'"</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 10:9">Revelation 10:9</a>–10</div>
        <div class="vtext">"Take the scroll… 'Take and eat it. It will make your stomach bitter, but in your mouth it will be sweet as honey.'"</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Ezekiel 9:4">Ezekiel 9:4</a>–6</div>
        <div class="vtext">"Pass through the city… and put a mark on the foreheads of those who sigh and groan over all the abominations."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 7:3">Revelation 7:3</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"Do not harm the earth or the sea or the trees, until we have sealed the servants of our God on their foreheads."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref">Ezekiel 38–39</div>
        <div class="vtext">The invasion of Gog of Magog, defeated by fire from heaven.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 20:7">Revelation 20:7</a>–10</div>
        <div class="vtext">"Gog and Magog… they marched up… and fire came down from heaven and consumed them."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Ezekiel 47:1">Ezekiel 47:1</a>–12</div>
        <div class="vtext">"Water was issuing from below the threshold of the temple… on the banks of the river there will grow… trees for food."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 22:1">Revelation 22:1</a>–2</div>
        <div class="vtext">"The river of the water of life, bright as crystal, flowing from the throne of God and of the Lamb… and the tree of life."</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="ornament">Isaiah</div>
    <p>
      Isaiah's visions of new heavens and new earth, of the holy city,
      of the Lord's reign over the nations, and of the fall of Babylon,
      shape the climax of Revelation.
    </p>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Isaiah 6:1">Isaiah 6:1</a>–4</div>
        <div class="vtext">"I saw the Lord sitting upon a throne, high and lifted up… seraphim… 'Holy, holy, holy is the Lord of hosts.'"</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 4:8">Revelation 4:8</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"Day and night they never cease to say, 'Holy, holy, holy, is the Lord God Almighty.'"</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Isaiah 65:17">Isaiah 65:17</a>, 25</div>
        <div class="vtext">"Behold, I create new heavens and a new earth… the wolf and the lamb shall graze together."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 21:1">Revelation 21:1</a>, 4</div>
        <div class="vtext">"I saw a new heaven and a new earth… he will wipe away every tear from their eyes."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Isaiah 13:21">Isaiah 13:21</a>, <a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 21:9">Revelation 21:9</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"Fallen, fallen is Babylon, and all the carved images of her gods he has shattered."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 14:8">Revelation 14:8</a>, <a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 18:2">Revelation 18:2</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"Fallen, fallen is Babylon the great, she who made all nations drink the wine of the passion of her sexual immorality."</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="ornament">Exodus</div>
    <p>
      The plagues of Egypt provide the template for Revelation's
      trumpet and bowl judgments, marking the new exodus God works
      through Christ. The seven seals/trumpets/bowls echo the
      plagues that brought Pharaoh down.
    </p>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Exodus 7:17">Exodus 7:17</a>–21</div>
        <div class="vtext">"The waters in the Nile will turn into blood."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 8:8">Revelation 8:8</a>, <a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 16:3">Revelation 16:3</a>–4</div>
        <div class="vtext">"A third of the sea became blood… every living thing died."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Exodus 10:21">Exodus 10:21</a>–23</div>
        <div class="vtext">"Darkness in all the land of Egypt three days."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 16:10">Revelation 16:10</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"Its kingdom was plunged into darkness."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Exodus 15:1">Exodus 15:1</a>–18</div>
        <div class="vtext">The song of Moses at the Red Sea.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 15:3">Revelation 15:3</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"They sing the song of Moses, the servant of God, and the song of the Lamb."</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="ornament">Zechariah</div>
    <p>
      Zechariah's night visions — the four horsemen, the lampstands and
      olive trees, the measuring line — surface throughout Revelation.
    </p>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Zechariah 1:8">Zechariah 1:8</a>–10, <a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 6:1">Revelation 6:1</a>–8</div>
        <div class="vtext">Horses of various colors, sent by the Lord through the earth.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 6:1">Revelation 6:1</a>–8</div>
        <div class="vtext">The four horsemen — white, red, black, pale — released at the breaking of the first four seals.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Zechariah 4:1">Zechariah 4:1</a>–14</div>
        <div class="vtext">A golden lampstand and two olive trees — the two anointed ones who stand before the Lord.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 11:3">Revelation 11:3</a>–4</div>
        <div class="vtext">"My two witnesses… these are the two olive trees and the two lampstands."</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="ornament">Genesis</div>
    <p>
      The Bible's first and last books are mirror images. What was lost
      in Genesis 3 is restored in Revelation 21–22.
    </p>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Genesis 2:9">Genesis 2:9</a>–10</div>
        <div class="vtext">"The tree of life in the midst of the garden… a river flowed out of Eden."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 22:1">Revelation 22:1</a>–2</div>
        <div class="vtext">"The river of the water of life… the tree of life."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Genesis 3:14">Genesis 3:14</a>–15</div>
        <div class="vtext">"I will put enmity between you and the woman… he shall bruise your head."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 12:9">Revelation 12:9</a>, <a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 20:10">Revelation 20:10</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"The great dragon was thrown down… and the devil… was thrown into the lake of fire."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Genesis 3:22">Genesis 3:22</a>–24</div>
        <div class="vtext">"He drove out the man… to guard the way to the tree of life."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 22:14">Revelation 22:14</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"Blessed are those who wash their robes, so that they may have the right to the tree of life."</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p style="margin-top: 30px; font-style: italic; color: var(--ink-faded);">
      Also significant: <strong>Psalm 2</strong> (Christ as king, ruling
      the nations with a rod of iron), <strong>Joel 2–3</strong>
      (Day of the Lord, locust army), <strong>Jeremiah 50–51</strong>
      (fall of Babylon), <strong>Amos 4</strong> (plagues), and many
      others.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- =========================== NT PARALLELS =========================== -->
  <section class="section" id="nt-parallels" data-section="nt-parallels">
    <div class="eyebrow">Section X</div>
    <h1>New Testament Parallels</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Revelation is not the Bible's only book about the end. Jesus' own
      teaching in the Gospels, Paul's letters, Peter, and Jude all
      contribute to a unified NT eschatology. Reading them together
      prevents both Revelation-only excess and Revelation-skipping
      neglect.
    </p>

    <h2>The Olivet Discourse</h2>
    <p>
      Jesus' great eschatological discourse in <strong>Matthew 24,
      Mark 13, and Luke 21</strong> — given in answer to the disciples'
      questions about the temple's destruction and "the end of the age"
      — provides the closest NT parallel to Revelation. Many of
      Revelation's images are already present there in seed form.
    </p>

    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 24:6">Matthew 24:6</a>–7</div>
        <div class="vtext">"Wars and rumors of wars… nation will rise against nation… famines and earthquakes."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 6:3">Revelation 6:3</a>–8</div>
        <div class="vtext">The four horsemen: conquest, war, famine, death.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 24:9">Matthew 24:9</a>–13</div>
        <div class="vtext">"You will be hated by all nations for my name's sake… the one who endures to the end will be saved."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 2:10">Revelation 2:10</a>, <a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 13:10">Revelation 13:10</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"Be faithful unto death… here is a call for the endurance and faith of the saints."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 24:29">Matthew 24:29</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"The sun will be darkened, and the moon will not give its light, and the stars will fall from heaven."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 6:12">Revelation 6:12</a>–13</div>
        <div class="vtext">"The sun became black as sackcloth, the full moon became like blood, the stars fell to the earth."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="parallel">
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 24:30">Matthew 24:30</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"They will see the Son of Man coming on the clouds of heaven with power and great glory."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow">⤳</div>
      <div>
        <div class="vref"><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 1:7">Revelation 1:7</a>, <a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 19:11">Revelation 19:11</a></div>
        <div class="vtext">"Behold, he is coming with the clouds, and every eye will see him."</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Paul's Eschatology</h2>

    <h3><a class="ref" data-ref="1 Thessalonians 4:13">1 Thessalonians 4:13</a>–18</h3>
    <p>
      Paul's most extended description of the Lord's return: a shout, the
      voice of an archangel, the trumpet of God, the dead in Christ
      rising, the living caught up to meet the Lord in the air.
      Revelation's trumpets and parousia visions assume this framework.
    </p>

    <h3><a class="ref" data-ref="2 Thessalonians 2:1">2 Thessalonians 2:1</a>–12</h3>
    <p>
      The "man of lawlessness" passage is the closest Pauline parallel
      to Revelation 13's beast. Paul describes a future apostasy, the
      revealing of a lawless one who exalts himself, his destruction
      by Christ at his coming. The dispensational and historic
      premillennial traditions read Rev 13's beast through this lens.
    </p>

    <h3><a class="ref" data-ref="1 Corinthians 15:20">1 Corinthians 15:20</a>–28, 50–58</h3>
    <p>
      Paul's resurrection theology: Christ's resurrection as firstfruits,
      the dead raised at his coming, "the last trumpet," all enemies put
      under his feet, and finally the Son delivers the kingdom to the
      Father. This is the framework within which Revelation 20–21
      operates.
    </p>

    <h3><a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 8:18">Romans 8:18</a>–25</h3>
    <p>
      Paul's vision of creation itself groaning, awaiting the
      revealing of the sons of God and its own liberation from
      decay. Revelation 21–22's new creation is Paul's hope made
      visible.
    </p>

    <h2><a class="ref" data-ref="2 Peter 3:3">2 Peter 3:3</a>–13</h2>
    <p>
      Peter's account of the day of the Lord coming "like a thief,"
      the heavens passing away with a roar, the elements dissolved,
      "new heavens and a new earth in which righteousness dwells."
      Revelation's catastrophic imagery and new-creation hope are
      Peter's hope expanded into a vision.
    </p>

    <h2>Jude 14–15</h2>
    <p>
      Jude quotes 1 Enoch on the Lord's coming "with ten thousands
      of his holy ones to execute judgment on all." Revelation 19's
      armies of heaven assume this vision.
    </p>

    <h2>The Gospel of John</h2>
    <p>
      Revelation shares many distinct images with the Fourth Gospel —
      the Lamb of God (<a class="ref" data-ref="John 1:29">John 1:29</a>, 36), living water (John 4, 7),
      light/darkness, Word of God as personal title, sheep and shepherd,
      vine-imagery, "I AM" sayings. Whether or not authored by the same
      hand, they breathe the same theological air.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- =========================== FATHERS =========================== -->
  <section class="section" id="fathers" data-section="fathers">
    <div class="eyebrow">Section XI</div>
    <h1>The Church Fathers</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      To read Revelation responsibly is to read it with the church
      across the ages, beginning with those who knew the Apostles
      themselves.
    </p>

    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 110</div>
        <div class="name">Papias of Hierapolis</div>
        <div class="desc">A disciple of John, according to Irenaeus. Held a vivid earthly millennial expectation, the earliest patristic witness to chiliasm. Quoted by Irenaeus and Eusebius.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 150</div>
        <div class="name">Justin Martyr</div>
        <div class="desc">In <em>Dialogue with Trypho</em> 80–81, defends the chiliast reading of Revelation 20 — a literal thousand-year reign in a restored Jerusalem — while acknowledging that "many good Christians" disagree. The first major theologian to interact extensively with Revelation.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 180</div>
        <div class="name">Irenaeus of Lyons</div>
        <div class="desc"><em>Against Heresies</em> Book 5 contains the most extensive 2nd-century treatment of Revelation. Irenaeus is the principal external witness to John's authorship and the late date (95). Premillennial. Sees the Beast as a future antichrist figure who will reign 3½ years.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 200</div>
        <div class="name">Tertullian</div>
        <div class="desc">North African Latin father. Premillennial. Identifies Babylon with Rome. His treatise <em>Against Marcion</em> defends the apostolic origin of Revelation.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 220</div>
        <div class="name">Hippolytus of Rome</div>
        <div class="desc">Wrote <em>On Christ and Antichrist</em>, an early systematic treatment of the antichrist figure drawing heavily on Revelation 13 and Daniel. Premillennial.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 230</div>
        <div class="name">Origen of Alexandria</div>
        <div class="desc">The great representative of allegorical/spiritual reading. Skeptical of chiliasm. Treats the visions of Revelation as portraying spiritual realities of the soul's progress and the church's pilgrimage rather than future earthly events. The first major idealist voice.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 260</div>
        <div class="name">Dionysius of Alexandria</div>
        <div class="desc">A pupil of Origen. Argued on stylistic grounds that the apostle John did not write Revelation — proposing a separate "John the Elder." His arguments shaped later Eastern doubt about the book's canonicity and authorship.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 270</div>
        <div class="name">Victorinus of Pettau</div>
        <div class="desc">Bishop, martyr under Diocletian, and author of the <strong>earliest surviving commentary</strong> on Revelation. Premillennial in original form. Introduced what would become "recapitulation theory" — the idea that the seven series (seals, trumpets, bowls) describe the same era from different angles, not strict chronological sequence.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 290</div>
        <div class="name">Methodius of Olympus</div>
        <div class="desc">Author of <em>Symposium of the Ten Virgins</em>. Held a chastened chiliasm and read Revelation 12's woman as the church.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 310</div>
        <div class="name">Lactantius</div>
        <div class="desc">Tutor of Constantine's son. His <em>Divine Institutes</em> Book 7 expounds a millennial vision drawn directly from Revelation. Last major Latin pre-Augustinian chiliast.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 325</div>
        <div class="name">Eusebius of Caesarea</div>
        <div class="desc">Court historian under Constantine. Listed Revelation as a "disputed" book (<em>antilegomena</em>), though acknowledged its widespread use. Influenced by Dionysius's authorship doubts. The Eastern church's hesitation toward the book begins here.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 380</div>
        <div class="name">Tyconius the Donatist</div>
        <div class="desc">A schismatic North African layman whose lost commentary on Revelation deeply influenced Augustine. Developed Victorinus's recapitulation reading and applied it to the millennium: the thousand years is the current church age. Bridge from premillennial to amillennial readings.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 410</div>
        <div class="name">Augustine of Hippo</div>
        <div class="desc"><em>City of God</em>, Book 20, is the watershed of Western interpretation. Augustine rejects literal chiliasm as a "ridiculous fable," reads Revelation 20's binding of Satan as accomplished by Christ at the cross, and the thousand years as the church age. This becomes the medieval Western consensus and the dominant Reformed view. Amillennialism, in essence, begins here.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 530</div>
        <div class="name">Primasius of Hadrumetum</div>
        <div class="desc">North African bishop whose Augustinian-Tyconian commentary on Revelation became a standard reference for medieval Latin readers.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 600</div>
        <div class="name">Andrew of Caesarea</div>
        <div class="desc">Cappadocian archbishop whose Greek commentary became the great Eastern Orthodox standard. Less literal than the early premillennialists; broadly idealist; preserves rich patristic interpretive tradition. The most influential commentary in the Greek-speaking East.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 730</div>
        <div class="name">The Venerable Bede</div>
        <div class="desc">Anglo-Saxon monk; his <em>Explanation of the Apocalypse</em> transmits Augustinian recapitulation to the medieval West. The first to systematically divide Revelation into seven parallel visions.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 950</div>
        <div class="name">Beatus of Liébana</div>
        <div class="desc">Spanish monk whose <em>Commentary on the Apocalypse</em> became the source for the famous illuminated "Beatus manuscripts" of medieval Spain — among the most spectacular illustrated Bibles ever produced.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p style="margin-top: 30px; font-style: italic; color: var(--ink-faded);">
      <strong>A pattern emerges:</strong> the ante-Nicene fathers were
      largely premillennial; Origen and Tyconius opened the door to
      symbolic/recapitulatory readings; Augustine swung the Western
      church decisively to amillennialism, which then dominated for
      a thousand years. The Eastern church, under Andrew of Caesarea,
      developed its own moderate idealist tradition. All this is
      <em>before</em> the Reformation reopens the question.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- =========================== THINKERS =========================== -->
  <section class="section" id="thinkers" data-section="thinkers">
    <div class="eyebrow">Section XII</div>
    <h1>Great Thinkers Through History</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      From the medieval visionaries through the Reformers and into
      the modern era, Revelation has been a school for theologians,
      mystics, exiles, and pastors.
    </p>

    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1200</div>
        <div class="name">Joachim of Fiore</div>
        <div class="desc">Calabrian abbot, mystic, prophet. His <em>Exposition of the Apocalypse</em> introduced a sweeping historicist framework: history is divided into three ages of Father, Son, and Spirit, with Revelation's seven seals corresponding to seven epochs of Christian history. Enormously influential — every later historicist reading owes him a debt.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1270</div>
        <div class="name">Thomas Aquinas</div>
        <div class="desc">The great scholastic. Broadly Augustinian/amillennial in eschatology. His <em>Summa</em> treats the antichrist as a personal future figure but rejects literal millennial speculation. Sober, measured, traditional.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1380</div>
        <div class="name">John Wycliffe</div>
        <div class="desc">"The Morning Star of the Reformation." His writings on Revelation identified the papacy with the antichrist of 2 Thessalonians 2 and the beast of Revelation 13 — beginning a Protestant historicist tradition that would dominate for three centuries.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1520</div>
        <div class="name">Martin Luther</div>
        <div class="desc">Initially doubted Revelation's apostolicity (1522 preface: "I miss more than one thing… Christ is neither taught nor known"). His 1530 revised preface embraced a historicist reading: the papacy is the beast, the prophesied apostasy is at hand. Luther's reading shaped Lutheran orthodoxy for generations.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1560</div>
        <div class="name">John Calvin</div>
        <div class="desc">Wrote commentaries on every NT book except Revelation. Privately amillennial, suspicious of speculative interpretation. Reportedly said Revelation was "the only book of the Bible I do not understand" — though his published works speak respectfully of it.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1600</div>
        <div class="name">Theodore Beza · Heinrich Bullinger</div>
        <div class="desc">Reformed successors of Calvin and Zwingli; both wrote substantial commentaries on Revelation in historicist Protestant form, identifying papal Rome with Babylon.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1645</div>
        <div class="name">Westminster Divines</div>
        <div class="desc">Drafted the <strong>Westminster Confession</strong>, whose original text identified the pope as "Antichrist, that man of sin and son of perdition" (25.6). Modern revisions have softened the language. The Confession is amillennial in its eschatology, anticipating "general resurrection" and "general judgment" at Christ's return.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1680</div>
        <div class="name">John Owen</div>
        <div class="desc">Puritan giant. His treatment of Revelation reflects a moderate historicism with strong attention to the suffering church. Sometimes considered an early proto-postmillennial.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1700</div>
        <div class="name">Daniel Whitby</div>
        <div class="desc">English clergyman whose <em>Treatise of the True Millennium</em> argued for a future "thousand years" of gospel triumph <em>preceding</em> Christ's return — the first clear modern formulation of postmillennialism, which would shape the Great Awakening.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1707</div>
        <div class="name">Isaac Newton</div>
        <div class="desc">The mathematician spent decades on biblical prophecy. His <em>Observations upon the Prophecies of Daniel and the Apocalypse of St. John</em> (published 1733) is rigorously historicist. Newton calculated detailed prophetic schemes still studied today.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1740</div>
        <div class="name">Jonathan Edwards</div>
        <div class="desc">Princeton theologian and pastor of the First Great Awakening. His <em>Notes on the Apocalypse</em> set Revelation within a sweeping postmillennial vision: the gospel will progressively triumph through history; the millennium is the church's great future age of flourishing before Christ's return. Edwards's postmillennialism shaped American evangelicalism.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1830</div>
        <div class="name">John Nelson Darby</div>
        <div class="desc">Anglo-Irish minister, founder of the Plymouth Brethren. The architect of <strong>dispensational premillennialism</strong> — including the pre-tribulational rapture as a distinct event from the second coming. Through the Scofield Reference Bible (1909), Darby's system became dominant in American evangelicalism for the 20th century.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1880</div>
        <div class="name">B.B. Warfield · Charles Hodge</div>
        <div class="desc">Princeton theologians of the late 19th century. Both robustly postmillennial. Warfield's essay "The Millennium and the Apocalypse" remains a landmark argument for symbolic/amillennial-postmillennial reading of Revelation 20.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1909</div>
        <div class="name">C.I. Scofield</div>
        <div class="desc">His <em>Reference Bible</em> embedded dispensational notes directly into the biblical text, distributing Darbyism to millions of pastors and lay readers. Probably the single most influential study Bible in American religious history.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1939</div>
        <div class="name">William Hendriksen</div>
        <div class="desc">Reformed pastor and scholar. His <em>More Than Conquerors</em> is the modern classic of amillennial idealist reading, popularizing progressive parallelism for the 20th-century church. Accessible, pastoral, theologically rich.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1955</div>
        <div class="name">C.S. Lewis</div>
        <div class="desc">Not a commentator on Revelation, but his eschatological vision — most powerfully in <em>The Last Battle</em> and the closing chapters of <em>The Great Divorce</em> — captures the new creation hope of Revelation 21–22 as well as any modern writer.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1970</div>
        <div class="name">George Eldon Ladd</div>
        <div class="desc">Fuller Seminary scholar. <em>A Commentary on the Revelation of John</em> (1972) recovered <strong>historic premillennialism</strong> as a serious scholarly position against dispensationalism's dominance. Held that the church passes through the tribulation.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1970</div>
        <div class="name">Hal Lindsey</div>
        <div class="desc"><em>The Late Great Planet Earth</em> sold tens of millions of copies, reading current events (especially the founding of Israel in 1948) as fulfilling Revelation. Mainstreamed pop-dispensationalism.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1993</div>
        <div class="name">Richard Bauckham</div>
        <div class="desc">St Andrews scholar. <em>The Theology of the Book of Revelation</em> (1993) and <em>The Climax of Prophecy</em> (1993) restored serious attention to Revelation's literary artistry, OT background, and pastoral theology. Among the most important Revelation scholars of the late 20th century.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 1999</div>
        <div class="name">G.K. Beale</div>
        <div class="desc">Author of the <em>NIGTC Commentary on Revelation</em> — the largest and most exhaustively researched English-language commentary ever produced on the book. Beale's eclectic/idealist-amillennial reading, with deep attention to OT background, has shaped a generation of pastors and scholars.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 2001</div>
        <div class="name">Dennis Johnson</div>
        <div class="desc"><em>Triumph of the Lamb</em>. Westminster Seminary California professor. The best concise pastoral exposition in the amillennial-progressive-parallelist tradition.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 2005</div>
        <div class="name">N.T. Wright</div>
        <div class="desc">Anglican bishop and scholar. <em>Revelation for Everyone</em> reads the book through partial-preterist and new-creational lenses, emphasizing first-century reference and ultimate cosmic renewal. Influential among readers tired of dispensational excess.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="event">
        <div class="year">c. 2010s</div>
        <div class="name">Sam Storms · Kim Riddlebarger · Anthony Hoekema</div>
        <div class="desc">Modern amillennial expositors. Hoekema's <em>The Bible and the Future</em> remains the standard accessible defense; Riddlebarger's <em>A Case for Amillennialism</em> is widely read; Storms's <em>Kingdom Come</em> argues amillennialism in detail.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- =========================== RESOURCES =========================== -->
  <section class="section" id="resources" data-section="resources">
    <div class="eyebrow">Section XIII</div>
    <h1>For Further Study</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      A curated reading list spanning the interpretive traditions.
      Listed not as endorsements of every view, but as windows into
      how serious Christians have read the Apocalypse.
    </p>

    <h2>Best Single-Volume Commentaries</h2>
    <div class="grid-2">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="label">Most Exhaustive</div>
        <h3>G.K. Beale</h3>
        <p><em>The Book of Revelation (NIGTC)</em>, 1999. Approximately 1,200 pages; sets the standard for Greek-text scholarship and OT background. Eclectic/amillennial. Demanding but rewarding.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="label">Best for Pastors</div>
        <h3>Dennis Johnson</h3>
        <p><em>Triumph of the Lamb</em>, 2001. Pastoral, accessible, theologically deep. Amillennial / progressive parallelist.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="label">Best Mid-Length</div>
        <h3>Grant Osborne</h3>
        <p><em>Revelation (BECNT)</em>, 2002. Eclectic with historic premillennial leanings. Balances exegesis and theology.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="label">Best Brief</div>
        <h3>Richard Bauckham</h3>
        <p><em>The Theology of the Book of Revelation</em>, 1993. Short, brilliant, focuses on literary and theological themes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="label">Historic Classic</div>
        <h3>William Hendriksen</h3>
        <p><em>More Than Conquerors</em>, 1939. The accessible classic of amillennial idealist reading. Still widely loved.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="label">Premillennial</div>
        <h3>Robert Mounce</h3>
        <p><em>The Book of Revelation (NICNT)</em>, revised 1998. Sober historic premillennial reading. Long a standard.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="label">Patristic</div>
        <h3>Andrew of Caesarea</h3>
        <p><em>Commentary on the Apocalypse</em> (early 7th c.). The great Eastern patristic commentary, finally available in modern English (Constantinou).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="label">Devotional</div>
        <h3>N.T. Wright</h3>
        <p><em>Revelation for Everyone</em>, 2011. Short, accessible chapters; partial-preterist new-creational reading.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>By Tradition</h2>
    <div class="grid-2">
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Preterist</h3>
        <p>R.C. Sproul, <em>The Last Days According to Jesus</em>; Kenneth Gentry, <em>Before Jerusalem Fell</em>; David Chilton, <em>The Days of Vengeance</em>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Historicist</h3>
        <p>E.B. Elliott, <em>Horae Apocalypticae</em> (1844, four vols); Matthew Henry's Commentary; Albert Barnes's Notes; Isaac Newton, <em>Observations upon the Prophecies</em>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Dispensational Futurist</h3>
        <p>John Walvoord, <em>The Revelation of Jesus Christ</em>; Robert Thomas, <em>Revelation: An Exegetical Commentary</em>; Charles Ryrie, <em>Revelation</em>; <em>The MacArthur Study Bible</em>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Historic Premillennial</h3>
        <p>George Eldon Ladd, <em>A Commentary on the Revelation</em>; Robert Mounce, <em>NICNT Revelation</em>; Wayne Grudem, <em>Systematic Theology</em> <a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 54:1">Revelation 54</a>–57.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Postmillennial</h3>
        <p>Jonathan Edwards, <em>A History of the Work of Redemption</em>; Loraine Boettner, <em>The Millennium</em>; Keith Mathison, <em>Postmillennialism</em>; Kenneth Gentry, <em>He Shall Have Dominion</em>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Amillennial / Idealist</h3>
        <p>Anthony Hoekema, <em>The Bible and the Future</em>; Kim Riddlebarger, <em>A Case for Amillennialism</em>; Sam Storms, <em>Kingdom Come</em>; Vern Poythress, <em>The Returning King</em>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>For Context</h2>
    <ul class="fancy">
      <li><strong>OT Background:</strong> G.K. Beale &amp; D.A. Carson (eds.), <em>Commentary on the New Testament Use of the Old Testament</em> — the chapter on Revelation alone is worth the price.</li>
      <li><strong>Apocalyptic Genre:</strong> John Collins, <em>The Apocalyptic Imagination</em>; D.S. Russell, <em>The Method and Message of Jewish Apocalyptic</em>.</li>
      <li><strong>Historical Setting:</strong> Leonard Thompson, <em>The Book of Revelation: Apocalypse and Empire</em>; Craig Koester, <em>Revelation and the End of All Things</em>.</li>
      <li><strong>Reception History:</strong> Christopher Rowland &amp; Judith Kovacs, <em>Revelation: The Apocalypse of Jesus Christ</em> (Blackwell Bible Commentaries) — surveys how Revelation has been read across the centuries.</li>
      <li><strong>Multiple Views volumes:</strong> C. Marvin Pate (ed.), <em>Four Views on the Book of Revelation</em>; Darrell Bock (ed.), <em>Three Views on the Millennium and Beyond</em>.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="ornament">❦ ✦ ❦</div>

    <h2>A Closing Word</h2>
    <p>
      Whatever school one favors, the central beatitude of the book
      remains constant:
    </p>
    <div class="pullquote">
      Blessed is the one who reads aloud the words of this prophecy,
      and blessed are those who hear, and who keep what is written
      in it, for the time is near.
      <cite><a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 1:3">Revelation 1:3</a></cite>
    </div>
    <p>
      Revelation was given to <em>bless</em>. To read it is itself a
      means of grace; to hear it together as the church is liturgy;
      to keep it is to walk faithfully now under the gaze of the
      Lamb who reigns. The book finally calls us not to a chart,
      but to a person — and to a city whose builder and maker is God.
    </p>
    <p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic; color: var(--oxblood); font-size: 22px; margin: 40px 0 10px;">
      Ἔρχου, Κύριε Ἰησοῦ.
    </p>
    <p style="text-align: center; color: var(--ink-faded); font-family: var(--smallcaps); letter-spacing: 0.18em; font-size: 13px; text-transform: uppercase;">
      Come, Lord Jesus. — <a class="ref" data-ref="Revelation 22:20">Revelation 22:20</a>
    </p>
  </section>

